  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees\n- Implementing screening mechanisms\n\n4. Legal regulations\n- Bank Secrecy Act\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n\n5. Risk assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Conducting ongoing due diligence\n- Implementing risk mitigation strategies\n\nFailure to comply can result in significant legal penalties, including:\n- Substantial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the financial system.",
